[1] Cholera - Uganda
Date: Wed 3 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: XinHuaNet.com [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-08/03/content_3305544.htm>

The Ugandan Ministry of Health has warned the public that the ongoing
cholera epidemic has affected 11 districts and caused a total of 220
cases and 56 deaths since the beginning of 2005. A statement was
quoted by Radio Uganda on Wed 3 Aug 2005 as saying that local
district and national epidemic response interventions have been
instituted in collaboration with development partners such as the
WHO, the Uganda Red Cross and many others.
At present, only the districts of Arua, Nebbi, Gulu and Kotido have
reported cases during the month of July 2005. The ministry would like
to inform the public that the present epidemic is caused by an
unusual strain that has not been commonly observed in Uganda.
"Therefore, the population is likely to be highly susceptible and, if
treatment is not sought promptly, the outcome could be severe," the
statement said.
It said: "the risk factors for the epidemic have been identified as
poor sanitation and hygiene, failure to wash hands with soap after
going to the latrine or after cleaning fecal matter from babies or
children, low latrine coverage and eating uncooked food and un-boiled
water."
The public is urged to conduct preventive measures, such as washing
hands with soap after going to the toilet or after handling fecal
matter, promptly burying the dead, reporting any suspected cases
promptly to health authorities and assisting suspected cholera
patients to get medical care as soon as possible.
"Delay to seek medical care has been the major under[lying] cause for
the deaths reported during the present epidemic," it said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
