[2] Cholera - Nigeria (Adamawa)
Date: Wed 3 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Vanguard (Lagos, Nigeria) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200508030139.html>

20 people confirmed dead, as cholera epidemic hits 3 Adamawa LGs
-----------------------------------------------
A cholera epidemic has broken out in 3 local government (LG) areas of
Adamawa State, with no fewer than 20 persons confirmed dead, while
scores of others are hospitalized, many of them on a danger list.
These are Numan, Lamurde and Guyuk local government areas. Unofficial
figures said the death toll might be higher, as the ravaging epidemic
continues to spread to the remotest areas of the affected local
governments.
Adamawa State House of Assembly confirmed the outbreak of the
epidemic and the death on the floor of the house on Tue 3 Aug 2005
and directed the Ministry of Health to immediately dispatch medical
personnel to the areas to contain the scourge. The lawmakers blamed
the outbreak on lack of portable water in the affected areas and
elsewhere in the state.
Contributing to deliberation on the outbreak as reported by members
representing the areas, the House directed its committee on health to
investigate the cause of the epidemic and recommend quickest measures
before the situation gets out of hand.
According to reports from the areas, 6 persons have died of the
epidemic in Lamurde, 10 in Guyuk and 5 in Numan, while many more are
receiving medical attention. Outbreak of epidemic and other water
borne related diseases have become a yearly scourge in Adamawa State,
more so among riverside communities. This yearly scourge, people
said, is caused by their dependence on water from the River Benue for
consumption and other domestic use at a time the river overflows its
banks following torrential rainfall.
Investigation by Vanguard revealed that the epidemic is fast
spreading to other Local Governments of Demsa, Shelleng, as well as
others in the neighboring states of Gombe, Taraba and Borno. A member
of the State House of Assembly representing Lamurde Constituency, Mr.
Vedeino Bamayi called on the Federal Government and private
organizations to intervene in the water crisis rocking Adamawa before
the state is completely ravaged by cholera.
[Byline: Umar Yusuf]
